{"cursor":"17303","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Surface charge' is the electric charge present at an interface. There are many\ndifferent processes which can lead to a surface being charged, including\nadsorption of ions, protonation/deprotonation, and the application of an\nexternal electric field. Surface charge causes a particle to emit an electric\nfield, which causes particle repulsions and attractions, and is responsible for\nmany colloidal properties. {{cite book |title=Physics and\nchemistry of interfaces |last1=Hans-Jurgen |first1=Butt |last2=Graf\n|first2=Karlheinz |last3=Kappl |first3=Michael |year=2006 |publisher=Wiley-VCH\n|location=Germany |isbn=978-3-527-40629-6 |pages=45, 55, 56, 76â82}}\n\nSurface charge practically always appears on an object surface when it is placed\ninto a fluid. All fluids contain ions, positive (cations) and negative (anions).\nThese ions interact with the object surface. This interaction might lead to the\nadsorption of some of them on the surface. If the number of adsorbed cations\nexceeds the number of adsorbed anions, the surface would gain total positive\nelectric charge.\n\nThere is another possible mechanism leading to surface charging. It is\ndissociation of the surface chemical group.\n","linknr":259,"url":"Surface_charge","recorded":1362485707,"links":21,"instances":["philosophy","interfacial","chemistry"],"pdf":["http://www.biophysics.org/Portals/1/PDFs/Education/ehrenstein.pdf","http://www.biophysics.org/Portals/1/PDFs/Education/ehrenstein.pdf"],"categories":["Electric charge"],"headings":["Surface charge density","Interfacial potential","Applications of surface charge","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/2/c/a2c8237c9beea55ec9ce12078c2a1878.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/3/bc3c57f70e2a9351f18d3f14b581f245.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/2/c224f6cb978d975f587c4a2f9e1db179.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Guoy-Chapman_Do